Docker Compose with MySQL and Volume

1. Introduction

This guide explains how to run a MySQL database using Docker Compose with persistent storage (volume).

Docker Compose allows us to define and run multi-container applications using a YAML file. Instead of running long Docker commands, 
  we define everything inside a "docker-compose.yml" file.

Then we start all services using a single command.



2. Why Use Docker Compose

Without Docker Compose we run containers like this:

docker run -d \
-v mysql-data:/var/lib/mysql \
-e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=root \
-p 3306:3306 \
mysql

But if a project has multiple containers (database, backend, frontend), managing them manually becomes difficult.

Docker Compose solves this by letting us define everything in a YAML configuration file.



3. Project Structure

Example project structure:

docker-mysql-compose
│
├── docker-compose.yml
└── README.md



4. Docker Compose File for MySQL with Volume

Create a file named:

docker-compose.yml

Add the following content:

version: "3.8"

services:

  mysql:
    image: mysql
    container_name: mysql-container

    environment:
      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root
      MYSQL_DATABASE: mydb
      MYSQL_USER: dev
      MYSQL_PASSWORD: dev123

    ports:
      - "3306:3306"

    volumes:
      - mysql-data:/var/lib/mysql

volumes:
  mysql-data:



5. Explanation of Each Section

Version

version: "3.8"

Defines the Docker Compose file format version.



Services

services:

Defines the containers that will run in the application.



MySQL Service

mysql:
  image: mysql

This tells Docker Compose to pull and run the MySQL image.



Container Name

container_name: mysql-container

Gives a custom name to the container.



Environment Variables

environment:
  MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root
  MYSQL_DATABASE: mydb
  MYSQL_USER: dev
  MYSQL_PASSWORD: dev123

These variables configure MySQL automatically when the container starts.

Meaning of variables:

Variable| Purpose
MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD| Root user password
MYSQL_DATABASE| Database created automatically
MYSQL_USER| Application user
MYSQL_PASSWORD| Password for the application user



Port Mapping

ports:
  - "3306:3306"

Maps the host port to the container port.

Format:

HOST_PORT:CONTAINER_PORT

This allows the host machine to connect to MySQL.



Volume Mapping

volumes:
  - mysql-data:/var/lib/mysql

This maps a Docker volume to the MySQL data directory.
MySQL stores database files in:

/var/lib/mysql

Mapping a volume ensures the database data is not lost when containers are removed.



Volume Declaration

volumes:
  mysql-data:

This tells Docker Compose to create a named volume.



6. Start the Containers

Run the following command inside the project directory:

docker compose up -d

Docker Compose will:

1. Pull the MySQL image
2. Create the container
3. Create the volume
4. Start the service



7. Check Running Containers

docker ps

You should see the MySQL container running.



8. Check Created Volumes

docker volume ls

You will see a volume similar to:-
docker-mysql-compose_mysql-data

Docker Compose automatically prefixes the volume with the project name.



9. Stop the Containers

docker compose down

This command stops and removes containers but keeps the volume.



10. Remove Containers and Volumes

docker compose down -v

This removes:

- Containers
- Networks
- Volumes



11. Advantages of Docker Compose

Docker Compose provides several advantages:

- Simplifies container management
- Allows running multiple services together
- Uses configuration files instead of long commands
- Makes development environments easy to reproduce



12. Summary

Docker Compose allows us to manage containers using a YAML configuration file.

In this setup:

- MySQL runs as a service
- Environment variables configure the database
- A Docker volume stores database data
- Containers can be started using a single command

This approach is commonly used in development and DevOps environments.
